45 to 25 Stone Street, north side, west from a point west of Mill Lane, to and including Broad Street. Also shown, is No. 90 Broad Street (5-story house, left), at the S.W. corner of Stone Street.

About 1925.

Gift of E.M. Jenks.

Mill Lane, north from South William, to and including Stone Streets. Also shown is Nos. 60-62 Stone Street, adjoining the S.E. corner of Hanover Square.

July 6, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

original_title: Manhattan: South William Street - Mill Lane
text:
(1)
South William Street, east from but not including Mill Lane, to and including Beaver Street (where 10-story building is seen being prepared for demolition). Also shown is William Street (left) north from Beaver to Wall Streets. The building at the apex is that of the Farmers Loan and Trust Co., at the N.E. corner of William and Beaver Streets, and is in process of being razed to make room for a new 59-story skyscraper, called the City Bank Farmers Trust Building.
July 6, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A part of the same, exposing to view the Beaver Street side of the Farmers Loan and Trust Co. Building and eliminating William Street.
July 6, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
The same, at a later date, showing the clearance created by the demolition of the Farmers Loan and Trust Co. Building (where steam shovels are working), and across it a part of the National City Bank Building. In the background are seen (left to right) the Bank of New York and Trust Co. and the National City Buildings.
August 24, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.
